@node Info "A few introductory words:"
@{fg shine}
  Introduction to A-Start (preview version):
@{fg text}
	 Before I start telling you about A-Start, I would like to remind
	 you that this is only a preview version, with which you will only get a
	 limited feel for what A-Start can do.  Many of A-Start's features are not
	 present yet.
		A-Start is a multi-function utility.  It is a handy alternative to
	 tool managers and program launchers, but that is not all.  Its GUI gives
	 you an easy and intuitive way to control and keep track of some of the most
	 important and often used functions of your system. For example editing your
	 preferences or like launching your favorite programs are now just a few
	 clicks away. You'll have fast access to your projects, whether it is
	 programming, graphics, or sound:  two clicks, and you are in your
	 programming-environment, paint program, or music editor editing your
	 project.
		Using A-Start, you can browse through your partitions in no time, and do
	 whatever you need to do with the files encountered.  A-Start recognizes
	 the file types for you, and will start your prefered viewer or editor.
	 All with beautiful graphics and relaxing sound(n/a yet).  But wait, 
	 there's more! Deleting or renaming files is a snap with A-Start!


  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode
@node Req "System Requirements"
@{fg shine}
  What you need in order to run A-Start:
@{fg text}
	 Kickstart 2.04:
				This version of Kickstart nowadays is no longer standard, 
				so get yourself OS3.1 if you are running an amiga under 3.0!

	 MagicWB:
				To make A-Start look its best, you need MagicWB colors.

	 Screen mode:
				It is recommended that you use a screen mode with a 1:1
				screen pixel aspect & a large page-size (min. 640*400).

	 Hard disk:
				A-Start is not very useful without a hard disk, and with
				today's hardware prices, every Amiga user should have one!
				HD's are to be thought of as standard equipment.

	 Font:
				You need the XHelvetica font, which comes with the Magic-
				WB package.

	 WBStart-handler:
				A-Start needs Stefan Becker's @{"WBStart-Handler" LINK WBStarter}:

  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode

@node features "What can A-Start do for you?"
@{fg shine}
  A-Start features:
@{fg text}
	 - Easy to use: pop-up windows and intuitive gadgets
	 - Graphically pleasing look-and-feel
	 - Easy control of your preferences
	 - Easy access to your most used programs
	 - Easy access to projects you are working on
	 - Fast file-browser always within reach
	 - Automatic recognition of file types
	 - Delete/rename files intuitive
	 - Much more...

	 Please remember that this describes what the A-Start preview can do:
	 the full version will have many more features.  Please see the @{"future" LINK future}
	 page for more information.


  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode

@node install
@{fg shine}
  How to install A-Start:
@{fg text}
	 To install this software, double-click on the install icon and
	 the installer will guide you through the installation.

@{fg shine}
	 PLEASE DO ALLWAYS USE THE INSTALLER SCRIPT
@{fg text}

		To enable running of A-Start on every BootUp after the initial
	 installation, copy the A-StartWBS program to your WBStartup
	 directory. Please make sure that the A-Start path is typed in
	 correctly in the only tooltype of A-StartWBS.info.


  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode

@node usage
@{fg shine}
  How to run A-Start:
@{fg text}
	 Two programs are included in this package:  the A-Start main pro-
	 gram, and the small A-StartWBS program.  Because the main program
	 has to reside in its own directory with specific subdirectories
	 it cannot be placed directly in your sys:wbstartup/ directory.
	 If you want A-Start to start every time you boot your system,
	 you may put the A-StartWBS program into sys:wbstartup/. (it will
	 run A-Start from the directory specified in its only tooltype.
	 Make sure this tooltype is properly set to be the A-Start home
	 directory)

	 For example:  APATH=dh1:utils/A-Start/

@{fg shine}
  How to use the @{"PREVIEW" LINK preview} version of A-Start
@{fg text}
	 First of all you have to start the program by double-clicking on
	 its icon, or by running it from the CLI.  A small button should
	 appear at the bottom left of your workbench screen (note that if
	 your workbench screen is not open, A-Start will open it).  Click
	 on that button, and the main window pops up, presenting you with
	 seven different selections (selected by moving the cursor over it):

	 @{" MyComputer   " LINK mycomp}  Browse through your mounted drives.
	 @{" UserProgs    " LINK progs}  Start your most often used programs.
	 @{" FileList     " LINK filelist}  Start your most important projects
	 @{" Utilities    " LINK utils}  Start a system utility program(n/a).
	 @{" Preferences  " LINK prefs}  Quicklink to your preferences directory
	 @{" Command      " LINK command}  Issue a CLI command
	 @{" Reboot (quit)" LINK reboot}  Quit A-Start/Reboot your Amiga (TM)
	 
	 @{" HotLists     " LINK hotlist}  Delete/Rename/Edit files
	 
  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode
@node mycomp
@{fg shine}
  MyComputer:
@{fg text}
	 After pressing this button, a window pops up showing all your mounted
	 disk devices by name.  Selecting one of the disk gadgets brings the
	 root directory of that disk to front.
		You may to your liking create hotlinks to directorys and display
	 them in this window. If you for example have a directory full of pictures
	 and often take a glance at them you may find it easier to create a
	 hotlink in order to get to that directory rather than to browse through
	 subdirectories after subdirectories. To create a hotlink just drag and
	 drop the corresponding ICON onto this window and the hotlink will be
	 created.




  @{" Back to usage " LINK usage}
@endnode
@node progs "Define your most used programs"
@{fg shine}
  UserProgs:
@{fg text}
	 This gadget brings your progs-window to front. This is a window where
	 all your favorite programs reside.  Drag the icon for the program you
	 wish to have fast access to, and drop it into this window:  it will
	 be redrawn, now containing your program.

	 It is not possible to drop drives or directories into the window, but
	 you may organize your programs even better, through "program independent" 
	 drawers:  Select the HotList-option 'Add Drawer' of any file in the 
	 UserProgs-window to add such a drawer.


  @{" Back to usage " LINK usage}
@endnode
@node filelist "A button to launch your projects fast"
@{fg shine}
  FileList:
@{fg text}
	 This works like the UserProgs window, but in here you may only put
	 projects you are currently working on.  A-Start will check the default
	 tool for the selected project, and load the default program.  This
	 allows for a rapid return to editing your source code again, after
	 for example your last test run crashed your system. Only project-icons
	 are allowed to be dropped into this drawer.

  @{" Back to usage " LINK usage}
@endnode
@node utils "This is not implemented yet!"
@{fg shine}
  Utilities:

	 In this version of A-Start, this window does nothing.
@{fg text}
	 In future versions this is where you have ultra-fast access to all
	 the important features to help you work better with your Operating
	 System.

  @{" Back to usage " LINK usage}
@endnode
@node prefs
@{fg shine}
  Preferences:
@{fg text}
	 This is a quicklink to sys:prefs/ for quick and easy (am I repeating
	 myself?) access to all the preferences programs of your Amiga(TM).

  @{" Back to usage " LINK usage}
@endnode
@node command
@{fg shine}
  Command:
@{fg text}
	 After pressing this button, a requester pops open where you may enter 
	 a CLI command, which A-Start will then execute. This is (almost) like 
	 pressing rCommand e on newer OS-versions.


  @{" Back to usage " LINK usage}
@endnode
@node reboot
@{fg shine}
  Reboot:
@{fg text}

	 You may shut down A-Start by clicking on this gadget and holding the
	 left mousebutton for one second pressed. After releasing, A-Start will
	 terminate.

	 To SoftBoot your machine simply double-click onto this gadget.
	
		In the prefs-editor you can enable a security-option, so that A-Start
		asks you if you really want to reboot/quit or not. 
		

  @{" Back to usage " LINK usage}
@endnode

