@node hotlist "The HotList"
@{fg shine}
	 HotList-How to make it pop up?:
@{fg text}

	 To make the HotList pop up, simply press the left mousebutton over the
	 icon (the small picture left of the name) of any File-entry and keep
	 it pressed. releasing the button selects the highlighted option.
	 
@{fg shine}
	 HotList-What to do with it?:
@{fg text}

	 The most important feature of the hotlist is that you can define for
	 each FileType (iff,gif,guide,lha,...) one or two functions additional
	 to the function, which is executed, when you select the entry. These
	 are called the 2nd and the 3rd function. In the prefs-editor you can
	 simply enter these two functions in the same manner you entered the
	 main-function. Additional to that you have to define the names for
	 these functions as they will appear under that name in the hotlist.
	 
	 Imagine for example a lha-file:
		
		The main function should be the command, which you most often will
		execute. Imagine browsing through your HD and finding a LHA-archive
		with a name you do not recognize. Wouldn't it be nice if you could 
		just double-click on it and see a list of what it contains? No 
		problem:  Just enter the function 'LHA l {f}' for the main-function
		of a LHA-archive. But what if you then find out that you have found
		the lha-archive you have been looking for and want to unpack it to 
		your Data-directory. With A-Start you do not have to start the CLI
		and type the unpack command in, no! Just enter for the 2nd function
		of a LHA-archive the name 'Unpack LHA' or something like that and
		for the function itself 'LHA x {f} dh1:Data/'. Then with the HotList
		you are able to unpack LHA's to your Data-directory. 
		 
		If you encounter for example a IFF-picture you most likely want to
		take a look at it and the decide if you want to load it into your 
		paint-program,right? The enter for the main-function 'Visage {f}'
		and for the 2nd function the name 'Paint iff' and for the function
		itself 'PPaint:PPaint {f}'. 
			
		It's as easy as that!
		
@{fg shine}
	 HotList-What else to do with it?:
@{fg text}
	
	 There aree three useful default-parameters defined for every HotList:
	 
	 -'Remove entry' removes a file from the UsrProgs or FileList-windows.
	 This was on earlier versions done with the 'D'-button
	 
	 -'Delete' markes the current file to be deletet, when the user closes 
	 the window in which the file is in. There is a security-option, which
	 will ask you if you really want to delete files, once the window is
	 being closed. Ofcourse you may remove the deletion-flag before closing
	 the window.
		The delete-option can not be used for directories or drives.
	 
	 -'Rename'. With this you can rename the current file or dir.
	
@endnode

@node PrefsP "The Prefs program"
@{fg shine}
	 Preferences:
@{fg text}
		
	You actually do not need a description of the prefs-program in this
	manual, because all buttons are described in the prefs-program itself.
	Just let the mouse-pointer rest for a second or two (depending on your
	MUI-settings) on the gadget you want to get information of.
	
	If you have problems to make your own FileTypes look at the pre-defined 
	ones and all should be clear.
				
  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode

@node WBStarter "Stefan Beckers WBStart-handler"
@{fg shine}
	 About WBStarter:
@{fg text}
	 WBStart-handler is a handler copyrighted and written by Stefan Becker.

	 Short Description:

	 WBStart is a handler wich lets you run programs in "WB-mode"
	 from CLI.  The program now thinks it has been started from the
	 workbench, by double-clicking on its icon.

	 A-Start NEEDS WBStart-handler. Most of you have it in your L: directory, 
	 but if it ain't, please get the WBStarter package from Aminet. A-Start 
	 does not use the WBStarter library, because it needs OS3.0 to function.

  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode
@node MUI "Magic User Interface"
@{fg shine}
  About Magic User Interface:
@{fg text}
	 MUI is shareware, copyrighted by Stefan Stunz.  You do not have to
	 register MUI in order to use the A-Start preferences program,
	 but I really think you should, because of the superb quality
	 of the MUI system.


  @{" Back to main " LINK main}
@endnode

